lans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Islay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Imlach  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Imlach","meanings":["Scottish (mainly Banffshire): topographic name from Gaelic <i>imleach</i> ‘marginal or marshy land’."]}]},{"name":"Aonghas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pronounced ‘<b>een</b>-yis’; from Celtic words meaning ‘one’ and ‘choice’. This is the name of an ancient Celtic god, and is first recorded as a personal name in Adomnan's ‘Life of St Columba’, where it occurs in the form <i>Oinogus(s)ius</i> as the name of a man for whom the saint prophesied a long life and a peaceful death. This is also almost certainly the name of the 8th-century Pictish king variously recorded as <i>Onnust</i> and <i>Hungus</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Aonghus","meanings":["Pronounced ‘<b>een</b>-yis’; from Celtic words meaning ‘one’ and ‘choice’. This is the name of an ancient Celtic god, and is first recorded as a personal name in Adomnan's ‘Life of St Columba’, where it occurs in the form <i>Oinogus(s)ius</i> as the name of a man for whom the saint prophesied a long life and a peaceful death. This is also almost certainly the name of the 8th-century Pictish king variously recorded as <i>Onnust</i> and <i>Hungus</i>."]},{"name":"Angus","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Scottish Gaelic name  <b>Aonghas</b>  . Though still having a Scottish flavour, it has been used increasingly in modern times also by people without Scottish connections."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Aonghas O'Cathan of Islay was born in 1225, in Scotland, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 daughters with King Guy O'Cathain - King of Keena